01:02:44.730 --> 01:02:49.270
&gt;&gt;Chris: But let me just give a further answer.

01:02:49.270 --> 01:02:54.829
What emerged as Hank said, was in a sense,
a synthesis of two key things.

01:02:54.829 --> 01:02:56.099
One of them had to do with healing.

01:02:56.099 --> 01:03:02.339
And so you heard me talk about how the project
was for me a chance to try to create a connection

01:03:02.339 --> 01:03:05.820
between these different segments of the African
American community.

01:03:05.820 --> 01:03:09.660
Who for historical reasons were separated
and needed each other.

01:03:09.660 --> 01:03:15.200
So that one has a sense of empowerment and
freedom to move through opportunities and

01:03:15.200 --> 01:03:16.260
the greater world.

01:03:16.260 --> 01:03:19.620
Others have a strong sense of community, belonging
to each other.

01:03:19.620 --> 01:03:21.839
And so, wanting to heal that.

01:03:21.839 --> 01:03:23.400
So healing became one theme.

01:03:23.400 --> 01:03:26.730
And that could have been the driving force
behind the whole project.

01:03:26.730 --> 01:03:28.690
But another one emerged that was really important.

01:03:28.690 --> 01:03:31.099
And that is representation.

01:03:31.099 --> 01:03:37.589
The opportunity of black men through this
format to speak and define themselves.

01:03:37.589 --> 01:03:41.880
Without an author telling them what to say,
and how to say it.

01:03:41.880 --> 01:03:46.900
And so those dynamics played out even within
a particular sequence.

01:03:46.900 --> 01:03:52.070
And that's what gives it such depth and richness,
I think.

